review_blob:
aroma: dark chocolates and earthy tones. slight coffee as well. 
appearance: pours a very dark red, almost black, with a creamy head of moderate thickness. 
taste: moderate bitterness, and sweetness and a slight savouriness. 
palate: the body is medium with an oily texture and a soft but lively carbonation.

i enjoyed this beer. moreso than the dobbelbock winter ale of theirs. was just a bit more bitter and chocolatey. 
a good beer

pours a dark red, nice brown-tan head that comes up quickly but isnt really all that solid. looks very attractive on first pour. 
aroma isnt that strong but there are chocolates, cherries, plums, slight caramel - lots of those malty smells coming through. a very slight freshness from the hops though too. some oakiness in there as well. so a bit complex, but they could all stand to do with a bit of an increase. 
relatively smooth to drink with a light to moderate bitterness and a light sweetness. 
palate is comfortable. slight carbonation, smooth texture and medium body. with an ok finish thats a bit bitter.
all round a pretty solid beer. 
because its marketed as a winter beer though, i guess i was expecting more from the body of the bitterness or the malts or even a bit more sense of the alcohol.

big aroma, citruses, caramels, herbs, lovely to smell. 
golden and cloudy to pour with a big strong head that recedes slowly to leave you with an attractive thick layer across it. 
moderately bitter and sweet. works perfectly though
palate: creamy and thick texture, in a full body. carbonation works well and there is a long comfortable finish both sweet and bitter.

i really enjoy the grand cru. a really good beer, that i feel can be had in any season

aroma is fruity and bright. reminded me of a lambic. a sense of oakiness to it as well. 
pours an orangey brown, and cloudy. head is light and recedes quite quickly.
light-med sweetness, and medium bitterness and lightly sour.
medium body, a really dry beer that ends with a lingering sweetness that makes u sip again. 
enjoyable. not my favourite trappist but it is very unique and different. worth a try

strong aroma; chocolate, toffee, and possibly turkish delight and rich cherries. 
rocky strong head, black in colour. 
much smoother than anticipated; medium bitterness, light sweetness.
velvety and smooth palate. adorable to the mouth. the after taste is sweet, a little bit and slightly burnt, but really lovely. 
a really good oatmeal stout. would love to be able to sit down to one of these every night of winter.

aroma: appley almost, citruses, with caramels and i sensed a sort of resinish sterility that wasnt overly unpleasant but still seemed to be there. 
appearance: pale gold, hazy with a white minimal head
taste: light sweetness, light-medium bitterness which is sharp but comfortable, perhaps a very light sourness to it
palate: light-medium body, a thin texture with an average carbonation. the finish has a bitterness to it that reminded me of tea. 
quite a pleasant beer. i enjoyed it quite a bit although, again, at $30 a bottle i dont know if id buy it again, but nevertheless enjoyable.

from what i remember as i had this a while ago and only made brief notes then. 
aroma: caramel, spruce
appearance: amber, clear, head was moderate but receded quickly
taste: light sweetness,medium bitterness
palate: medium body, oily texture, average to soft carbonation with a bitterish finish
quite a good english bitter. but for the price of it out here i dont think buy it again.

Aroma: caramel, floral, herbs, leather
Appearance: amber, hazy, head is light and white
Taste: it has light bitterness and light-medium sweetness
Palate: medium body, oily texture, soft carbonation, and a pleasant, sweet and bitter lingering after taste.

pour nice, head not that thick. nice aroma, coffee and chocolate. smooth malted flavours, chocolate, caramel, coffee; but still lacking the real body that may have made it a very good beer. 
nice beer, not as big as i was hoping for though. still smooth and rich enough to be enjoyable though
